Facial Expression Recognition
Facial Expression Recognition (FER) is a research area within computer vision that focuses on detecting and interpreting human emotions from facial cues. It combines image processing, pattern recognition, and machine learning to infer affective states from static images or video streams, supporting applications in human-computer interaction, security, and psychology.

Key Facts
Domain: Computer vision, affective computing

Input: Facial images or video sequences

Output: Emotion categories (e.g., happiness, sadness, anger) or continuous affect values

Techniques: Deep learning, CNNs, RNNs, transformer models

Applications: Healthcare, driver monitoring, social robotics, marketing analytics

Background
Early FER systems relied on manual feature extraction based on the Facial Action Coding System (FACS), which decomposes expressions into muscle movements. With advances in machine learning, especially deep convolutional neural networks (CNNs), models began automatically learning discriminative facial features from large datasets, significantly improving accuracy and robustness.

Methods and Architectures
Modern FER pipelines typically include face detection, alignment, feature extraction, and emotion classification. CNN-based models such as VGGNet and ResNet variants dominate static image FER, while recurrent and transformer-based architectures capture temporal dynamics in video. Attention mechanisms and multi-modal fusion (e.g., with voice or physiological data) enhance context understanding.


